speech rights to include algorithmic outputs, courts understood speech as mediated through technology. Speech thus became disarticulated from individual speakers. By outlining how legal definitions of speech are indelibly dependent on technology, Petersen demonstrates that future innovations such as artificial intelligence will continue to restructure speech law in ways that threaten to protect corporate and institutional forms of speech over the rights and interests of citizens.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2022) 0aCommunicationxEffect of technological innovations onzUnited States. 0aFreedom of expressionzUnited States. 0aFreedom of speechzUnited States. 0aMass media and technologyxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aTechnological innovationsxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  ainformation theory.  apost-human speech.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076691240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478021827zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478021827423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478021827/original  a978-3-11-076691-2  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles